00:34:43.110 --> 00:34:47.170
So there's a couple
things that you can do.

00:34:47.170 --> 00:34:50.580
One is you compress the volume.

00:34:50.580 --> 00:34:53.040
And the reason why
this works is that,

00:34:53.040 --> 00:34:55.739
if you note you have four
molecules over here-- 1

00:34:55.739 --> 00:34:57.690
plus 3 going to 2.

00:34:57.690 --> 00:35:00.780
So if you compress
that volume down,

00:35:00.780 --> 00:35:04.600
you're going to shift it toward
the fewer number of molecules,

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:05.220
which is 2.

00:35:05.220 --> 00:35:07.390
So that shifts it
toward products.

00:35:07.390 --> 00:35:10.230
The other thing that they do is
they actually remove products

00:35:10.230 --> 00:35:11.530
from the reaction.

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:14.760
So they liquefy out the
product at some point.

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:17.040
And when you remove
the product, that also

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:19.080
shifts the reaction
toward more products

00:35:19.080 --> 00:35:20.590
to minimize the stress.

00:35:20.590 --> 00:35:22.530
So these are two of the
things that are done.

00:35:22.530 --> 00:35:25.980
So you have to
have high pressure

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:29.250
to compress that volume
down and high temperatures.

00:35:29.250 --> 00:35:31.870
So this process costs
a lot of energy.

00:35:31.870 --> 00:35:35.910
So we spend a lot of
energy in this country

00:35:35.910 --> 00:35:37.470
doing this reaction.

00:35:37.470 --> 00:35:40.680
And the reason why
is because it's

00:35:40.680 --> 00:35:43.670
really hard to split
nitrogen. So what kind of bond

00:35:43.670 --> 00:35:46.164
does nitrogen have, N2 have?

00:35:46.164 --> 00:35:46.955
Triple bond, right.

00:35:46.955 --> 00:35:47.859
It's very hard.

00:35:47.859 --> 00:35:48.900
It has a high bond order.

00:35:48.900 --> 00:35:50.730
It's very hard to
break that bond.

00:35:50.730 --> 00:35:53.430
And so you really have
to work at breaking it.

00:35:53.430 --> 00:35:57.300
So if you're doing
industry, there's

00:35:57.300 --> 00:35:59.190
lots of nitrogen in the air.

00:35:59.190 --> 00:36:01.080
So a lot of it is available.

00:36:01.080 --> 00:36:04.860
But it's just very hard to
utilize it to fix that nitrogen

00:36:04.860 --> 00:36:06.420
into another form.

00:36:06.420 --> 00:36:09.540
So lots of nitrogen in the air.

00:36:09.540 --> 00:36:11.610
Nitrogen is needed
by all living things,

00:36:11.610 --> 00:36:14.880
but it's really hard to
break that triple bond.

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:18.270
But if you're a bacteria, you
have a much easier time doing

00:36:18.270 --> 00:36:21.000
this than if you are a person.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.320
And bacteria have an
enzyme called nitrogenase.

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:27.280
Adding the "-ase"
means it's an enzyme.

00:36:27.280 --> 00:36:29.850
So this is an enzyme
that works on nitrogen.

00:36:29.850 --> 00:36:31.470
Most people call it
"nit-raw-genase,"

00:36:31.470 --> 00:36:33.390
but it's really "nitrogen-ace."

00:36:33.390 --> 00:36:34.620
And it splits nitrogen.

00:36:34.620 --> 00:36:38.760
And it does this by these
really complex metallocofactors.

00:36:38.760 --> 00:36:40.440
Lots of metals in here.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:42.150
You have iron and molybdenum.

00:36:42.150 --> 00:36:44.190
You also have inorganic sulfur.

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:46.720
And it's those d-orbitals
that let you do this.

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.560
So you can use high
temperatures, high pressure.

00:36:49.560 --> 00:36:52.740
Or you can get a transition
metal with beautiful d-orbitals

00:36:52.740 --> 00:36:54.152
to do your work for you.

00:36:54.152 --> 00:36:55.860
And a lot of people
are trying to come up

00:36:55.860 --> 00:36:59.650
with their own catalyst inspired
by nature to get this to work.

00:36:59.650 --> 00:37:01.950
So this is an ongoing
area of research.

